[2] California
Date: Wed 6 Jun 2007
Source: The Sacramento Bee [edited]
<http://www.sacbee.com/103/story/207420.html>

Health investigators do not know how long it will take them to trace the
source of the _E. coli_ that tainted 75 000 pounds (about 34 020 kg) of
beef processed at United Food Group LLC's Vernon processing plant, state
officials said Tue 5 Jun 2007.
The bacterium, _E. coli_ O157:H7, sickened a dozen people in 5 states and
Canada, including 3 in Southern California.
United Food Group, one of the nation's largest ground beef manufacturers,
voluntarily recalled the beef Sun 3 Jun 2007, after health officials from
California, Colorado, and the CDC (US Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention) discovered the bacteria in samples of the meat. From United's
Vernon plant, the product was shipped to retail distribution centers in 5
western states and ultimately made it into store freezers in 11 states.
The recall targeted 10-pound (4.5 kg) casings and 5- (2.27 kg), 2- (0.91
kg) and 1-pound (0.45 kg) tubes of Moran's All-Natural fine ground beef and
sirloin; 2- and 1-pound tubes of Inter-American Products ground beef; and
3-pound (1.36 kg) tubes of ground beef from Southern California grocer
Stater Bros. Markets.
[byline: Darrell Smith]
